messages.content:
Bittensor is a project that decentralizes processing power.
Google, for example, centralizes all of their compute power internally (i.e. google only uses their millions and millions of dollars of compute power for themselves).
Bittensor decentralizes this. Effectively, you can take more compute power from all across the world and point that to specific models in need of serving.

Now, at this stage, those models are being chosen, albeit, at random by miners (made up of registered members of the overall community).
At a later stage, the idea is that a validator would set up a particular model to be served, of which, miners would step in and serve that model in order to contribute valuable information that builds upon that model

No, but way back when I was newer to Bittensor, on a slow re-reg (luck), I also had the thought "is it biased against my dereged Hotkey?" -- definitely not so.

To clear up any misconceptions:
1. Any hotkey/coldkeys you create won't be banned or remove. They'll always be listed on the network.
2. You need to register your hotkey on the network. By doing so, you are effectively kicking someone else's registered hotkey off the network and taking their UID.
3. Your hotkey must then be used to either serve models or validate.
4. Given the competitive nature of this project, your hotkey MUST contribute greater value than the bottom 10% in order to retain your right for that hotkey being registered.
5. If you underperform, your hotkey's UID will be de-registered, assigning it to someone else to give them a chance to perform better.
6. If you keep registered, you need to continue finding ways to outperform the bottom 10% to maintain your position. Obviously, you'd be better outperforming 50%> so you are incentivized better
This project is built around incentivizing those who contribute high quality information to the network in order to build out high quality AI models

embeds.title: Btcli Commands
embeds.description:
**$btcli --help**: btcli commands list
**$btcli stake --uid [uid]**: The stake value for a given UID 
`  Example: $btcli stkae --uid 5  `
**$btcli inspect --uid [uid]**: Neuron info for a given UID 
`  Example: $btcli inspect --uid 5  `
**$btcli metagraph --raw**: The csv file of neuron info 

**$btcli incentive**: The plot of sorted incentive value 
**$btcli incentive --raw**: The csv file of incentive value 
**$btcli incentive --raw [--[ascending/descending]]**: The csv file of (optionally) sorted incentive values 
`  Example: $btcli incentive --raw --ascending  `
**$btcli incentive --uid [uid] --range [days]**: The incentive values of a certain uid for last days 
`  Example: $btcli incentive --uid 5 --range 5 `
